Hmm....MEMF_PUBLIC is defined as memory that must not be mapped, swapped or
otherwise made non-addressable...apparently it's for interrupts.  There is
also:

MEMF_LOCAL = Memory that doesn't disappear after a soft reboot
MEMF_24BITDMA = Memory within the range of 24bit DMA Zorro2 devices
MEMF_KICK = Contains kicktags and other funny exec things that I'm gonna
have no end of fun finding out what they do this afternoon ;)
MEMF_REVERSE = Grabs a chunk of memory from the back of the pool, rather
than the start.
MEMF_NO_EXPUNGE = Will not cause an "expunge" when a memory allocation
fails, I assume that means it won't attempt to flush unused devices etc.

