> 
> Use MEMF_ANY. By default it will try to allocate fast then chip. I'm 
> not sure what public is for, but it is defined differently and not 
> explained in the OS includes.

Well MEMF_ANY is 0.

And you should not use MEMF_PUBLIC if the memory area you are allocating
is used only from your task. But ANY MEMORY AREA WHICH IS USED BY
INTERRUPTS OR OTHER TASKS SHOULD INCLUDE IT. This kind of cases are
requesters, messages, all displayable GFX like bitmaps and OS structures
(well you shouldn't allocate most of OS stuff by yourself, but those that
you
do YOU MUST INCLUDE IT).

The thing what this does is it will force this type of memory to the
physical memory of the machine even if the task that owns the memory is
swaped off the physical memory due to waiting state in it.

Well this is not used at the moment, but if future versions do then your
program is either a memory hoging or an unstable program.

