> In that case,how is it different from a normal (non-compiler directive) command?
> Is it because you couldn't put it in a function or a subroutine and call it?
> What would happen if you did? (hmm,guess I can test that eh?;)

You could put it in a statement or function, although you'd be more 
likely to get errors of the type "Only available in Blitz mode" (when 
running) or something. Unless you done:

Function blah
   blitz
   ; stuff
   amiga
End Function

The problem with AMIGA, QAMIGA and BLITZ commands is that they are 
not solely compiler directives. True compiler directives would be 
things like CNIF, use of constants (i.e. #BLAH) because these only 
have an effect on the program during compilation and are only used by 
the compiler.

Those three commands could be broken down into something like this:

BLITZ:

Turn off multitasking     ; actual program code, executed at run-time
Take over display         ; actual program code, executed at run-time
Inform compiler to use Blitz specific versions of commands ; compiler 
directive part

So I wouldn't really call them compiler directives, because they 
produce code in the final executable.


