miami.library, which is created by miami on startup gives just such an
option.  It's how Voyager detects whether it is online or not.  And it does
indeed involve the "mi0" interface.

You see, the "lo0" interface is your "localhost" adaptor, and as such will
always be online.  "mi0" however is the standard miami's interface to the
big wide world.

Using a 'MiamiIsOnline_("mi0")' will return either a 0 for offline, or a 1
for online.  And the connection itself can be controlled using the
MiamiOnOffline() call.

Below is an assemblified version of MiamiIsOnline(), note that you will need
to open and close miami.library v12 yourself.

Function MiamiIsOnline{*interface.l}
;                          a0
  SHARED MiamiBase.l
  PutReg a6,a_six.l
  GetReg d6,MiamiBase.l
  MOVE.l d6,a6

  MOVE.l d0,a0

  JSR -210(a6)
  GetReg d6,a_six.l
  MOVE.l d6,a6
  PutReg d0,result.l
  AsmExit
  Function Return result.l
End Function

