Subject: @{b}Re: Initialising memory.@{ub}

On 29-Feb-00, David McMinn wrote.

> Hi Tony
> 
>> I have a chunk of memory which I wish to fill with %FF.    Any
>> thoughts on the most efficient way.
> 
> Dunno about efficient but you could use FillMem address,size[,value] 
> from one of the RI libs I think. It'll be probably as fast as you 
> could get, because it'll just be a for...next loop in asm.
> 
>> Move %FF to the first byte then CopyMem First byte to second byte for
>> a length of size-1.     If so, what's the syntax for that?
> 
> Not possible. When copying memory, it has to be the same size for 
> source and destination.
> 
>> The other part is an allocated memory area which I need to
>> (repeatedly) clear to %00.    The other option for this is to free it
> 
> Use FillMem again.
> 
> If you don't want to go to the hassle of having another library stuck 
> onto your exe, then you could try this (untested, and the apostrophes 
> may be the wrong way round, i'm using a PC) statement:
> 
> Statement _FillMem{address.l, bytesize.l, value.b}
> ._FillMem:
>     MOVEA.l    d0,a0            ; put address into address register
>     '_for1:
>         MOVE.b    d2,(a0)+    ; store value at address and increase add
>         SUBQ.l    #1,d1        ; decrease size of area to fill
>         BNE        '_for1        ; if not zero, do next byte
>     AsmExit
> End Statement
>

Well this can be optimized, but it depends from the size and alignment of
the area to be filled.

Here is one optimized version.

Start ad have to be in long boundary. the fill size is rounded down to
nearest 16 byte boundary, and it can't be larger than 65536*16.
The used fill value is LONGWORD, so it will make stripy fill if the bytes
in the long are not equal to each other.

But execution will be much faster than the above one.

statement fill{ad.l, siz.l, val.l}
  move.l d0,a0
  lsr.l  #4,d1
  subq.l #1,d1
  blt    exit

loop:
  move.l d2,(a0)+
  move.l d2,(a0)+
  move.l d2,(a0)+
  move.l d2,(a0)+
  dbra   d1,loop

exit
  asmexit
end Statement

