I presume that you're using the bsdsocket through by having
bsdsocket.library1 setup in Blitz? If so, then I'd have to agree with
Anton, you have probably opened the library yourself in your code. Blitz
opens the library for you at the start of the code, which is bad for
bsdsocket.library as it's not always there ;) I *would* recommend not
using bsdsocket.library1 but using the TCPFuncs in SocketFuncs.lha as
this gives you control over opening and closing bsdsocket.library. It's
a bit more hassle, but infinitely better and safer. If you run your prog
when miami isn't running and then run miami you will enjoy crashes as
things are. 

If you're positive you're not doing anything silly, try writing a small
program and seeing if that works. If it does, then there's a problem in
your other program. If not, then post it to the list in ascii format and
we can all have a muse over it.

Cheers,

Roger
